Example 1Source <pre><code> 
 ```javascript lp:chart addsrc="Example 1"
 labels = [
   'January',
   'February',
   'March',
   'April',
   'May',
   'June',
 ];
 data = {
   labels: labels,
   datasets: [{
     label: 'My First dataset',
     backgroundColor: 'rgb(255, 99, 132)',
     borderColor: 'rgb(255, 99, 132)',
     data: [0, 10, 5, 2, 20, 30, 45],
   }]
 };

 config = {
   type: 'line',
   data: data,
   options: {}
 };

 ```
</code></pre> <p>Using python:</p> Example 2Source <p> </p> <pre><code> 
 ```python lp:python|chart addsrc="Example 2"
 import datetime

 labels = [datetime.date(1900, m+1, 1).strftime('%B') for m in range(7)]

 data = {
   'labels': labels,
   'datasets': [{
     'label': 'My First Python Dataset',
     'backgroundColor': '#8bd125',
     'borderColor': '#8bd125',
     'data': [0, 10, 5, 2, 20, 30, 45],
   }]
 }

 result = {
   'type': 'line',
   'data': data,
   'options': {}
 }
 ```
</code></pre> <p>Restrictions in Python</p> <p>Example 2 is a simply delivering the stringified <code>result</code> as <code>config</code> dict into javascript. Means, you have no dynamic possibilities, using javascript functions.</p>
